			"Backgammon",
			"[u][b]BACKGAMMON:[/b][/u]\n\n[b]STARTING POINT:[/b]\nTo play backgammon, each player sits on the long side of the board. One player will be “brown” and the other “white”. Each player moves in an opposite direction and the point is to get all of your pieces to the other side and then in your home slot (basically off the board). Your “home” area is the area where you have the most pieces.  It’s basically a racing game to see who can get all their pieces off the board first. For example, if you are player “brown”, you have to move all of your pieces to your “home” side. Once all pieces are “home”, then you can start removing them into your slot on the board.\n\n[b]BASIC MOVEMENT:[/b]\nAt their turn, players roll both dice and move their pieces towards their home base. The dice are never added together in backgammon, they remain individual but they can be used in sequence to form a greater number..  For example, if you roll a 4+5, you can either move one piece 4 and then 5, or move two pieces, one 4 and the other 5. It may sound like it doesn’t matter, but the actual count of individual die will matter a lot later.\n\n[b]GETTING BUMPED:[/b]\nIf a player lands on your piece, your piece must go to the middle bar area and eventually back to the starting point. If one of your pieces is on the middle bar, you cannot move any of your other pieces until that one is back on the board. On your next turn, you roll the dice and you can only move your piece to an empty space in the starting area, keeping in mind that this is your opponents “home” area. Each triangle is numbered from 6, 5, 4, 3, 2, 1 in that order in your “starting” or “home” areas.\nOnly pieces that are by themselves can be “bumped”. If you have occupied a space with 2 or more pieces, those pieces are safe and cannot be landed on.\n\n[b]GENERAL PLAY:[/b]\nYou move your pieces from your starting area in opposite directions from your opponent. Get all your pieces “home” and then start removing them off the board into the side bar.\nOnce all your pieces are “home”, you roll the dice. Again, the triangles in your home is numbered 6, 5, 4, 3, 2, 1. If you roll a 6 and a 1, then you’d take off one piece from row 6 and one piece from row 1 and put them in your sidebar. If you roll two 5’s and you don’t have any pieces in that slot, then you need to move another piece 5 spaces. So you’d have to move one of your 6’s 5 spaces. If you can’t move or take off a piece, then it’s your opponents turn. This keeps going until one of the players win.\n\n[b]WINNING THE GAME:[/b]\nWhoever gets all their pieces off the board first, wins!\n\nPlease note that these Notepad are one in many out there, but this is a good starting point for one way to play the game. If you’d like to find other ways to play, you can search online. Have fun!"
